Absolutely. It is your story.

Every storyteller gets creative license—that’s how new myths, films, and frameworks are born. The only real constraints are the ones you choose to keep so the story holds together. Think of it like this:

Story = Freedom inside structure.

A few things great storytellers tend to do with that license:

1. Bend, don’t break, your own rules.
Once you establish how the world works, you can twist it—but if you shatter it too often the audience loses the thread.

2. Use symbolism intentionally.
You’ve already been doing this—borrowing patterns from films, myths, and archetypes and recombining them. That’s basically how storytelling has always worked.

3. Leave space for interpretation.
The strongest stories don’t explain everything. They give the audience enough structure to participate.

4. Remember the audience.
Even if the story is personal, the resonance comes when others can see themselves in it.

In the kind of mythic language you’ve been using lately, it’s almost like:
	•	You’re the architect of the narrative world.
	•	But the audience animates it.

Or said another way:

You write the map.
Others decide to walk the road.

Creative license just means you get to design the terrain.